define a function for selecting a xline, iline or twt slice and pivoting data for easy display¶

In [4]:
def slicer(df, attr, val, z = "data"):
    if attr in df.columns:
        df_slice = df.loc[df[attr] == val]
    else:
        df_slice = df
    if attr == "twt":
        return df_slice.pivot(index = "iline", columns = "xline", values = z)
    elif attr == "xline":
        return df_slice.pivot(index = "twt", columns = "iline", values = z)
    elif attr == "iline":
        return df_slice.pivot(index = "twt", columns = "xline", values = z)
    else:
        raise Exception("attribute not recognised")

define a function for displaying a slice¶

In [5]:
def displayer(arr_2d, vmini = -2, vmaxi = 2, colour = "gray"):
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize = (10, 10))
    ax.imshow(arr_2d, cmap = colour, vmin = vmini, vmax = vmaxi)
    return plt.show(fig)

define a function to perform 1D k-means clustering using amplitude of a 2D slice of seismic¶

In [7]:
def KM_cluster_1d(df, attr, val, clusters):
    sliced = slicer(df, attr, val).stack()
    index_names = sliced.index.names
    vals = sliced.reset_index().values.tolist()
    
    clusters = KM(n_clusters = clusters).fit_predict(np.array(vals)[:,2].reshape(-1, 1))
    
    for sublist, value in zip(vals, clusters):
        sublist.append(value)
            
    return slicer(pd.DataFrame(vals, columns = [index_names[0], index_names[1], "data", "cluster"]), attr, val, z = "cluster")

define a function to perform 3D k-means clustering using a 2D slice of seismic (x, y, amplitude).¶

dimensions of different units must be normalised such that no one dimension dominates the clustering, hence "twt_scale" and "scale_amp"¶

In [9]:
def KM_cluster_3d(df, attr, val, clusters, scale_twt = 0.2, scale_amp = 2000):
    sliced = slicer(df, attr, val)
    index_names = sliced.stack().index.names
    nested_list = []
    for i, row in sliced.iterrows():
        for col in sliced.columns:
            if attr == "twt":
                nested_list.append([i, col, row[col] * scale_amp])
            else:
                nested_list.append([i * scale_twt, col, row[col] * scale_amp])

    vals = sliced.stack().reset_index().values.tolist()
    
    clusters = KM(n_clusters = clusters).fit_predict(np.array(nested_list))
    
    for sublist, value in zip(vals, clusters):
        sublist.append(value)
            
    return slicer(pd.DataFrame(vals, columns = [index_names[0], index_names[1], "data", "cluster"]), attr, val, z = "cluster")
